<subsection xml:id="subsubsec-multiplying-vectors-by-scalars" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Multiplying Vectors by Scalars</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.9 Vectors 1
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </introduction>
        <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcome</title>
                    <p>Multiply vectors by scalars to change magnitude and/or direction</p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <li component="lesson-plan">Grade Level: 10</li>
        <li component="lesson-plan">Estimated Duration: 40 minutes</li>
        <p component="lesson-plan">
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Know</title>
                    <p>How scalar multiplication affects a vector's magnitude and direction (positive, negative, and zero scalars)</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Do</title>
                    <p>Multiply vectors by positive, negative, and zero scalars; simplify vector expressions involving scalar multiplication</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Apply</title>
                    <p>Use scalar multiplication to solve problems involving scaling of forces and velocities</p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/vectors-1/multiplying-vectors-by-scalars.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/vectors-1/step-by-step-guide_multiplying-vectors-by-scalars.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />


    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery (15 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Anchor Activity: Discovering Scalar Multiplication</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            Organise students into groups of 2–3. Distribute graph paper, rulers, and pencils. Guide students through the activity below.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teacher Role During Discovery:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Circulate among students, ensuring they draw vectors correctly with arrows.</p></li>
                <li><p>Ask probing questions: <q>How does <m>\overrightarrow{AC}</m> compare to <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m>? What is the relationship?</q></p></li>
                <li><p>For struggling students: <q>Let us measure. <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m> is 2 units long. How long is <m>\overrightarrow{AC}</m>? Is it twice as long?</q></p></li>
                <li><p>For early finishers: <q>What if we multiply by 3? Draw a vector 3 times as long. What if we multiply by <m>-1</m>?</q></p></li>
                <li><p>Guide students to articulate: <em>Multiplying a vector by a positive number makes it longer; the direction stays the same.</em></p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Guiding Questions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li><p>What are the coordinates of vector <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m>? Of vector <m>\overrightarrow{AC}</m>?</p></li>
                <li><p>How does the length of <m>\overrightarrow{AC}</m> compare to <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m>?</p></li>
                <li><p>Do the vectors point in the same direction?</p></li>
                <li><p>What happens to a vector when you multiply it by 2? By 3?</p></li>
                <li><p>What do you think happens if you multiply by <m>-2</m>?</p></li>
                <li><p>What happens if you multiply by 0?</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <activity xml:id="auto_ihlzedjo">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_zti7ghqk">
            <p xml:id="auto_ehgu6kde">
                <alert>Work in groups</alert>
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task xml:id="auto_xem94r1e">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_423jejbb">
                    On a graph paper, draw the <m>x</m> axis and <m>y</m> axis.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_j36bycmj">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_p1ypfxgk">
                    Draw a directed line passing through point <m>A(0,2)</m> and <m>B(2,2)</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_lyv1qs1i">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_37opcyqd">
                    From point <m>B(2,2)</m>, draw directed line to point <m>C(4,2)</m>. 
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_ep4s0ouq">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_26t0q3t3">
                    Determine the coordinate representations of <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{AC}</m>..
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_dl796cmd">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_mwwuuyia">
                    How does <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m> relate to <m>\overrightarrow{AC}</m>?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_2s533p7e">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_alqx1hlk">
                    Discuss and share your findings with the rest of the class.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </activity>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction (10 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            After students have shared their findings from the anchor activity, formalise the rules for scalar multiplication using the Key Takeaway content below.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Scalar Multiplication Rules to Emphasise:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Scalar <m>k</m></cell>
                    <cell>Effect on Vector</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>k \gt 0</m></cell>
                    <cell>Same direction, magnitude multiplied by <m>k</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>k \lt 0</m></cell>
                    <cell>Opposite direction, magnitude multiplied by <m>|k|</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>k = 0</m></cell>
                    <cell>Zero vector (no magnitude, no direction)</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>k = 1</m></cell>
                    <cell>Vector unchanged</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>k = -1</m></cell>
                    <cell>Direction reversed, same magnitude</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Scaffolding Strategies to Address Misconceptions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Misconception</cell>
                    <cell>Clarification</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Multiplying by 2 adds 2 to each component</cell>
                    <cell>No — it multiplies each component by 2</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Negative scalar makes the vector smaller</cell>
                    <cell>No — it reverses direction and may change magnitude</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Multiplying by 0 keeps the vector the same</cell>
                    <cell>No — it creates a zero vector with no magnitude</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Direction always stays the same</cell>
                    <cell>No — negative scalars reverse the direction</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <p xml:id="auto_dl939ry7">
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_ju26u4ay">
        <term>Positive Scalar</term>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_wmyzshdo">
        In <xref ref="multiplication-vectors-scalar"/>, the vector <m>\mathbf{PQ}</m> is represented
        as <m>\mathbf{a}</m>.
        When we multiply <m>\mathbf{a}</m> by a positive scalar, say <m>2</m>,
        the length of the vector doubles, making it <m>\mathbf{2a}</m> as shown in <xref ref="multiplication-vectors-scalar-1"/>. 
        The direction of the vector remains unchanged, but its magnitude increases.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="multiplication-vectors-scalar">
        <caption></caption>
        <image width="30%">
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>  
            <latex-image>  
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}
                    
                    \draw[thick,-|] (0,0) -- (2,0);
                    \draw[thick,|-] (2,0) -- (4,0);
                    \node[left] at (0,0) {$\mathbf{P}$};
                    \node[right] at (4,0) {$\mathbf{Q}$};
                    \node at (2.5,0.3) {$\mathbf{a}$};
                    
                    % Draw arrows at the middle of the lines
                    %\draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (-1,1) -- (0,2);
                    \draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (2,0) -- (2.3,0);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image> 
        </image>
    </figure>
    <p xml:id="auto_ecxvba07">
        In <xref ref="multiplication-vectors-scalar-1"/>, the vector <m>\mathbf{PN}</m> is given by:
        <m>\mathbf{PN} = \mathbf{a} + \mathbf{a} = 2\mathbf{a}</m>.
        This means <m>\mathbf{PN}</m> has the same direction as <m>\mathbf{PQ}</m>, but its magnitude
        twice that of <m>\mathbf{PQ}.</m>
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="multiplication-vectors-scalar-1">
        <caption></caption>
        <image width="70%">
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>  
            <latex-image>  
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}
                    
                    \draw[thick,|-] (0,0) -- (2,0);
                    \draw[thick,-|] (2,0) -- (4,0);

                    \draw[thick,|-] (4,0) -- (6,0);
                    \draw[thick,-|] (6,0) -- (8,0);

                    %\draw[thick,|-] (8,0) -- (10,0);
                    %\draw[thick,-|] (10,0) -- (12,0);

                    \node[below] at (0,0) {$\mathbf{P}$};
                    \node[below] at (4,0) {$\mathbf{Q}$};
                    \node[below] at (8,0) {$\mathbf{N}$};

                    \node at (2.5,0.3) {$\mathbf{a}$};
                    \node at (6.5,0.3) {$\mathbf{a}$};
                    %\node at (10.5,0.3) {$\mathbf{a}$};
                    
                    % Draw arrows at the middle of the lines
                    \draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (2,0) -- (2.3,0);
                    \draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (6,0) -- (6.3,0);
                    %\draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (10,0) -- (10.3,0);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image> 
        </image>
    </figure>
    <p xml:id="auto_uj31gaud">
        <term>Negative Scalar</term>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_8eb40cdd">
        Consider the vector <m>\mathbf{AB}</m>,denoted as <m>\mathbf{a}</m>, in <xref ref="multiplication-vectors-negative-scalar-1"/>
        The vector points to the right and has a magnitude of <m>\mathbf{a}</m>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="multiplication-vectors-negative-scalar-1">
        <caption></caption>
        <image width="50%">
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>  
            <latex-image>  
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}
                    
                    \draw[thick,|-|] (0,0) -- (4,0);

                    \node[below] at (0,0) {$\mathbf{A}$};
                    \node[below] at (4,0) {$\mathbf{B}$};

                    \node at (2,0.4) {$\mathbf{a}$};
                    
                    % Draw arrows at the middle of the lines
                    \draw[-{Latex[length=2.5mm]}] (2,0) -- (2.3,0);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image> 
        </image>
    </figure>
    <p xml:id="auto_zmnvf55s">
        In <xref ref="multiplication-vectors-negative-scalar-2"/>, the 
        vector <m>\mathbf{AB}</m> is obtained by multiplying <m>\mathbf{AB}</m>
        by <m>-2</m>, giving:
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_l1c7xi4q">
        <me>
            \mathbf{AC} = \mathbf{-2} \times \mathbf{a} = \mathbf{-2a}
        </me>
        
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_n9aqp9i1">
        This means that <m>\mathbf{AC}</m> has <alert>twice</alert> the magnitude of <m>\mathbf{AB}</m>,
        but its direction is <alert>reversed</alert>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="multiplication-vectors-negative-scalar-2">
        <caption></caption>
        <image width="70%">
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>  
            <latex-image>  
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}
                    
                    \draw[thick,|-] (0,0) -- (2,0);
                    \draw[thick,-|] (2,0) -- (4,0);

                    \draw[thick,|-] (4,0) -- (6,0);
                    \draw[thick,-|] (6,0) -- (8,0);

                    %\draw[thick,|-] (8,0) -- (10,0);
                    %\draw[thick,-|] (10,0) -- (12,0);

                    \node[below] at (0,0) {$\mathbf{A}$};
                    \node[below] at (4,0) {$\mathbf{B}$};
                    \node[below] at (8,0) {$\mathbf{C}$};

                    \node at (2.5,0.3) {$\mathbf{-a}$};
                    \node at (6.5,0.3) {$\mathbf{-a}$};
                    %\node at (10.5,0.3) {$\mathbf{a}$};
                    
                    % Draw arrows at the middle of the lines
                    \draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (2.3,0) -- (2,0);
                    \draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (6.3,0) -- (6,0);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image> 
        </image>
    </figure>
    <p xml:id="auto_fljw6sx7"> 
        Multiplying a vector by a <alert>negative scalar</alert> reverses its direction,
        making it point in the <alert>opposite direction</alert>. 
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_wpzvuzi3">
        <alert>Zero Scalar</alert>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_1pmhsmlm">
        When a vector <m>\mathbf{a}</m>, as shown in <xref ref="multiplication-vectors-zero-scalar-1"/>,
        is multiplied by <m>0</m>, its magnitude becomes <m>0</m>, resulting in a <alert>zero vector</alert>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="multiplication-vectors-zero-scalar-1">
        <caption></caption>
        <image width="50%">
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>  
            <latex-image>  
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}
                    
                    \draw[thick,|-|] (0,0) -- (4,0);

                    \node[below] at (0,0) {$\mathbf{P}$};
                    \node[below] at (4,0) {$\mathbf{Q}$};

                    \node at (2,0.4) {$\mathbf{a}$};
                    
                    % Draw arrows at the middle of the lines
                    \draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (2,0) -- (2.3,0);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image> 
        </image>
    </figure>
    <p xml:id="auto_saxtpriu">
        <me>
            \mathbf{a} \cdot 0 = 0
        </me>
    </p>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application (10 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            Walk students through the worked example below. Emphasise the systematic approach: distribute the scalar, then combine like terms.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teacher Prompts:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li><p><q>What does <m>3\mathbf{u}</m> mean?</q> (Multiply every term in <m>\mathbf{u}</m> by 3.)</p></li>
                <li><p><q>How do we combine <m>6\mathbf{p} + 2\mathbf{p}</m>?</q> (Add the coefficients: <m>8\mathbf{p}</m>.)</p></li>
                <li><p>Remind students this is the same as simplifying algebraic expressions — collect like terms.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <example xml:id="auto_egjibz4y">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_0595mcoy">
                Given the vectors <m>u = 2p + 5q</m> and <m>v = p - 3q</m>, express <m>3u + 2v </m> in terms of <m>p</m> and <m>q:</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_p67ufqpk">
                Substitute the given expressions for u and v.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_lga11ayu">
                <md>
                    <mrow> 3u + 2v \amp = 3(2p + 5q) + 2(p - 3q) </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = 6p + 15q + 2p - 6q </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_33x6d4d3">
                Combine like terms (terms with p and terms with q).
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ahn5w0wk">
                <md>
                    <mrow> 3u + 2v \amp = (6p + 2p) + (15q - 6q) </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = 8p + 9q </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment (5 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Exit Ticket</alert> — Students complete the following questions individually.
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li><p>Simplify: <m>5\mathbf{x} + 3\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{z} + 2(3\mathbf{x} - \mathbf{z}) + (8\mathbf{x} - 6\mathbf{y})</m></p></li>
                <li><p>Simplify: <m>(\mathbf{a} - \mathbf{b}) + (\mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a}) + (\mathbf{b} - \mathbf{c})</m></p></li>
                <li><p>Given <m>\mathbf{x} = 3\mathbf{m} - \mathbf{n}</m> and <m>\mathbf{y} = \mathbf{n} + 4\mathbf{m}</m>, express <m>3\mathbf{x}</m> in terms of <m>\mathbf{m}</m> and <m>\mathbf{n}</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>Given <m>\mathbf{x} = 3\mathbf{m} - \mathbf{n}</m> and <m>\mathbf{y} = \mathbf{n} + 4\mathbf{m}</m>, express <m>6\mathbf{x} - 9\mathbf{y}</m> in terms of <m>\mathbf{m}</m> and <m>\mathbf{n}</m>.</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Answer Key (Teacher Reference):</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li><p><m>19\mathbf{x} - 3\mathbf{y} - 3\mathbf{z}</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>\mathbf{0}</m> (zero vector)</p></li>
                <li><p><m>9\mathbf{m} - 3\mathbf{n}</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>-18\mathbf{m} - 15\mathbf{n}</m></p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <exercises xml:id="exercises-multiplication-of-vectors-by-a-scalar">
        <exercise xml:id="auto_a5pmhqxy">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_95sizryf">
                    Simplify the following:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_78iddq4x">
                    <ol xml:id="auto_pdhtjj70" marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_fbffqutj">
                            <p xml:id="auto_8f16859s">
                                <m>5x + 3y - z + 2(3x - z) + (8x - 6y)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_2r3kppmp">
                            <p xml:id="auto_su7d294c">
                                <m>(\mathbf{a} - \mathbf{b}) + (c - \mathbf{a}) + (\mathbf{b} - c)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_hm62k6pp">
                            <p xml:id="auto_ootkdkp2">
                                <m>4m - 2n + 5(k - m) + 2(m + n)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)" cols="3">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>19x - 3y - 3z</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>0</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>m + 5k</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_4b6dh2gj">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_lv55wwfu">
                    Given that <m>x = 3m - n</m> and <m>y = n +4m</m>, express 
                    the following vectors in terms of <m>m</m> and <m>n:</m>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_3d5kgdgu">
                    <ol xml:id="auto_q5rk7c0u" marker="(a)" cols="2">
                        <li xml:id="auto_f3ge034w">
                            <p xml:id="auto_w2h7ibf6">
                                <m>3x</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_ib6eyzoi">
                            <p xml:id="auto_2cnrcysv">
                                <m>\frac{2}{3} y</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_6c7ns3s8">
                            <p xml:id="auto_2bo56l1q">
                                <m>6x - 9y</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_zu2s08kj">
                            <p xml:id="auto_h8ni1qwh">
                                <m>3y - x</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>9m - 3n</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\frac{8}{3}m + \frac{2}{3}n</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>-18m - 15n</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>9m + 4n</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_6zjn921x">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_guwn33xv">
                    A pentagon <m>ABCDE</m> with <m>\overrightarrow{AB} = m</m>, <m>\overrightarrow{BC} = n</m>, and 
                    <m>\overrightarrow{CD} = k</m>. Express the following vectors in terms of <m>m</m>, <m>n</m>, and <m>k:</m>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ymxwi7nn">
                    <ol xml:id="auto_sg4npxi3" cols="3" marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_ktqq1ai9">
                            <p xml:id="auto_vesglm6z">
                                <m>\overrightarrow{AC}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_5daqgotr">
                            <p xml:id="auto_qsd1rh63">
                                <m>\overrightarrow{AD}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <!-- <li xml:id="auto_u4y28cc0">
                            <p xml:id="auto_rfrfrqr2">
                                <m>\overrightarrow{AE}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li> -->
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>m+n</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>m+n+k</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
        <p>
            <alert>For Struggling Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Provide pre-drawn vectors with labels.</p></li>
                <li><p>Use colour coding: one colour for original vector, another for scaled vector.</p></li>
                <li><p>Provide step-by-step calculation templates.</p></li>
                <li><p>Start with simple positive scalars (2, 3) before introducing negative scalars.</p></li>
                <li><p>Pair struggling students with confident problem solvers.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>For On-Level Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Encourage students to create their own scalar multiplication problems.</p></li>
                <li><p>Ask students to explain why negative scalars reverse direction.</p></li>
                <li><p>Provide mixed practice with positive, negative, and zero scalars.</p></li>
                <li><p>Challenge students to simplify complex vector expressions.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>For Advanced Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Explore scalar multiplication in three dimensions.</p></li>
                <li><p>Investigate unit vectors (vectors with magnitude 1).</p></li>
                <li><p>Challenge: Prove that scalar multiplication is distributive, i.e. <m>k(\mathbf{a}+\mathbf{b}) = k\mathbf{a}+k\mathbf{b}</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>Explore applications in computer graphics (scaling transformations).</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Extension Activity: Force Vectors in Physics</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            Work in pairs. You push a box with a force vector <m>\mathbf{F} = \binom{10}{5}</m> N. Calculate: <m>2\mathbf{F}</m> (push twice as hard), <m>-\mathbf{F}</m> (opposite direction), and <m>0\mathbf{F}</m> (stop pushing). Plot all force vectors on graph paper and calculate their magnitudes.
        </p>
    </axiom>
